<DIV CLASS="c5"><BR><BR><P CLASS="c37"><SPAN CLASS="c31">n1&nbsp; Associate Professor of Law, Drexel University College of Law; JD, University of Pittsburgh; PhD, Arizona State University; LLM University of Wisconsin Law School. Many thanks to my esteemed colleagues, old and new, who offered a wealth of intellectual insight into the development of this project. I am indebted to offer special thanks to my best friend and coauthor Dr. Tryon Woods, my mentors Thomas J. Davis, Al Brophy, Russell Jones, Ray Diamond, and my new dean and colleagues at the Drexel Earle Mack School of Law. I owe special thanks to my muse whose support for my work remains indescribable. Finally, I wish to thank two law journals for their support and guidance. Thank you to the editorial staff of the </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c38">Journal of Race, Gender, and Poverty</SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c31"> at the Southern University Law Center, for inspiring what occurs in the following pages, and special thanks to the editorial staff at the </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c38">Seattle Journal for Social Justice</SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c31"> for their patience and support in sharing our work with the entire world.</SPAN></P>
</DIV>
<DIV CLASS="c5"><BR><BR></DIV>
<DIV CLASS="c5"><BR><BR><P CLASS="c37"><SPAN CLASS="c31">n2&nbsp; Assistant Professor of Criminology, Sonoma State University; BA, Wesleyan University; MS, Arizona State University; PhD, University of California, Irvine. Thank you to my colleague and coauthor, Donald Tibbs, and to the editorial staff at the </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c38">Seattle Journal of Social Justice</SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c31"> for sharing and supporting the spirit expressed in this project. My appreciation to those who have come before me (including those cited in the following pages), to those who struggle against violence of all kinds everywhere, and to those who daily chose love over fear, building a new tomorrow from the ground up. In this vein. I dedicate my work to my children, Naomi Marie and Assana Simone.</SPAN></P>
